</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="75" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,341,1094,1120]" box="[227,341,1094,1120]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,341,1094,1120]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,341,1094,1120]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1437,1140,1271]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[227,415,1140,1166]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Stroborineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[227,415,1140,1166]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Stroborineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[429,542,1140,1166]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
combines the morphological features of the apparently ancestral genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[227,344,1176,1201]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[227,344,1176,1201]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(simple whorl profile and spiral lines on the flank) and descendant genera such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1884" box="[1296,1437,1175,1201]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Stroboceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1296,1437,1175,1201]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Stroboceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ryckholt" authorityYear="1852" box="[263,413,1210,1236]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Vestinautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[263,413,1210,1236]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Vestinautilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(pronounced ventrolateral shoulder with sharp longitudinal ridges and submarginal ventral grooves).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[226,1437,1310,1441]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[227,415,1310,1336]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Stroborineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[227,415,1310,1336]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Stroborineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[422,529,1310,1336]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[683,800,1311,1336]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[683,800,1311,1336]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the more pronounced ventrolateral shoulder, which is reinforced by some raised longitudinal ridges, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[957,1074,1346,1371]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[957,1074,1346,1371]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is rounded. In addition, the submarginal ventral longitudinal groove, which in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[814,931,1381,1406]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[814,931,1381,1406]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only present on the juvenile stage, is still distinct in 
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[351,539,1415,1441]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Stroborineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[351,539,1415,1441]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Stroborineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[546,653,1415,1441]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the middle growth stage.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1436,1480,1576]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[227,415,1480,1506]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Stroborineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[227,415,1480,1506]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Stroborineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[428,541,1481,1507]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1884" box="[713,854,1480,1506]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Stroboceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[713,854,1480,1506]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Stroboceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ryckholt" authorityYear="1852" box="[922,1072,1480,1506]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Vestinautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[922,1072,1480,1506]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Vestinautilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the absence of the strong longitudinal ridges and broad longitudinal grooves that cause a polygonal whorl profile in these two genera. Instead, 
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[419,607,1550,1576]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Stroborineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[419,607,1550,1576]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="75">Stroborineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[614,721,1550,1576]" pageId="8" pageNumber="75" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
merely has spiral lines on the flanks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
